he DLA systems and Galactic halo had di erent enrichment histories. To assess the impact of dust obscuration, we present estimates of the dust-to-gas ratios for the DLA sight lines and crudely calculate dust extinction corrections. The dis-tribution of extinction corrections suggests that the e ects of dust obscuration are minimal and that the population of " " missing {\"{I}}{\"{I}} damped systems has physical characteristics similar to the observed sample. We update our investigation on the chemical evolution of the early universe in neutral gas. The results are in good agreement with our previous work, but we emphasize two di erences : (1) the unweighted and N(H I){\`{E}}weighted [Fe/H] mean metallicities now have similar values at all epochs except z [ 3.5, where small number statistics dominate the N(H I){\`{E}}weighted mean ; and (2) there is no evolution in the mean [Fe/H] metallicity from z \ 1.7 to 3.5 but possibly a marked drop at higher redshift. We conclude with a general discussion on the physical nature of the DLA systems. We stress the uniformity of the DLA chemical abundances which indicates that the protogalaxies identiÐed with DLA systems have very similar enrichment histories, i.e., a nearly constant relative contribution from Type Ia and Type II super-novae. The DLA systems also show constant relative abundances within a given system, which places strict constraints on the mixing timescales of the damped systems and may pose a great challenge to the protogalactic clump scenarios favored by hierarchical galaxy formation.},
